    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i keep getting this \"Connection Reset by Peer\" error on my ec2 instances in us-east-1. it only happens intermittently and usually during peak traffic. i checked the security groups and everything looks theoretically fine but the logs are driving me crazy. \n\nhere is a snippet from cloudwatch:\n2023-10-27T14:22:01Z iid: 4922-X | status: 502 | error: connection reset by peer | client_ip: 192.168.1.45\n\nany idea what might be causing this? specifically looking at network config or security groups.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "A \"Connection Reset by Peer\" during peak traffic often suggests the connection is being terminated by the other end, not just a simple firewall block. Since your security groups look fine, this could be related to resource exhaustion on the EC2 instance itself, like running out of ephemeral ports or hitting application-level timeouts. It's also possible that a load balancer or NAT gateway is timing out the connection prematurely under heavy load. You should investigate instance CPU/memory utilization and application logs for signs of service overload during those peak times.",
      "source": "target",
