      "role": "user",
      "content": "yeah that makes sense. i'll look into the NAT gateway metrics. it just feels so random though, like it's almost like something is intentionally messing with the connection only when things get busy. do you think there's any scenario where a configuration could act \"erratically\" or \"unpredictably\" like that without a clear error log? maybe some kind of silent failure?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Silent failures in networking are frustratingly common and often stem from subtle capacity limits rather than explicit errors. One possibility is an upstream service or intermediate network device throttling connections, which might manifest as a reset without logging the specific cause. Another scenario is TCP connection table exhaustion on the instance or the gateway itself, which acts unpredictably under stress. Look closely at the session counts reported by your NAT gateway and any any connection limits configured on your application server.",
      "source": "target",
